        {
            "id": "edfbd7fe3e7843ff9306d",
            "questionText": "A baseball is thrown from the ground at an angle of $!$\\theta = 30^\\circ$!$ with an initial velocity of $!$u = 30\\,\\text{m/s}$!$. Neglecting air resistance, determine the horizontal range of the baseball. Use $!$g = 9.8\\,\\text{m/s}^2$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "00b19914a0e841bfa681c",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by resolving the initial velocity into its horizontal component. Identify the correct formula that relates the horizontal component $!$u_x$!$ to the initial velocity $!$u$!$ and the angle $!$\\theta$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "6549c13e-d336-4760-899a-1964b1b38828"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$u_x = u \\cos \\theta$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$u_x = u \\sin \\theta$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$u_x = \\frac{u}{\\cos \\theta}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "2c62a5231b924b9b8adfb",
                    "stepText": "Now, let's determine the time of flight using the vertical component of the motion. Identify the proper formula that relates the total time of flight $!$T$!$ to the vertical component of the initial velocity and gravity $!$g$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "976c240a-1fbe-4cc3-bec4-a1cd6c0c9f6a"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\frac{2u \\sin \\theta}{g}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\frac{u}{g}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\frac{u \\sin \\theta}{g}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "31be09e38f55468f89f71",
                    "stepText": "Great work! Now calculate the horizontal range by multiplying the horizontal component of the velocity by the time of flight. Provide the numerical result along with its units.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "79.5"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "4dfd857b-d6d7-4d02-927d-822401187e9f"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "9c25f991e83b4b9d9064c",
            "questionText": "A delivery drone starts its journey at the origin, $!(0,0)!$. It first flies $!$100 \\, \\text{m}$!$ east, then $!$50 \\, \\text{m}$!$ north, and finally $!$25 \\, \\text{m}$!$ west. Calculate the final displacement from the origin in meters.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "aa5e3509c6a54dbc9887f",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by finding the final horizontal coordinate. The drone moves east and then west. Compute the net change in the x-direction.",
